'''Paleoenzymology''' (British: palaeoenzymology) is the study of prehistoric life through the properties of [[enzymes]] present in those organisms. Ancient enzymes can be [[Ancestral sequence reconstruction|reconstructed]] if their [[Protein sequence|sequences]] can be inferred from the sequences of current enzymes. Such inferrence is possible through [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] techniques such as [[Maximum Likelihood|maximum likelihood]] and [[Bayesian inference in phylogeny|Bayesian inference]].

== Examples ==
One example is the reconstruction of [[thioredoxin]] enzymes from up to 4 billion year old organisms.<ref name=":0">{{cite journal|last=Perez-Jimenez|first=Raul|author2=Alvaro Inglés-Prieto|author3=Zi-Ming Zhao|author4=Inmaculada Sanchez-Romero|author5=Jorge Alegre-Cebollada|author6=Pallav Kosuri|author7=Sergi Garcia-Manyes|author8=T Joseph Kappock|author9=Masaru Tanokura|date=3 April 2011|title=Single-molecule paleoenzymology probes the chemistry of resurrected enzymes|url=http://www.nature.com/nsmb/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nsmb.2020.html|journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology|volume=18|issue=5|pages=592–6|doi=10.1038/nsmb.2020|pmid=21460845|accessdate=3 April 2011|author10=Arne Holmgren|author11=Jose M Sanchez-Ruiz|author12=Eric A Gaucher|author13=Julio M Fernandez|pmc=3087858}}</ref> Whereas the chemical activity of these reconstructed enzymes were remarkably similar to modern enzymes, their physical properties showed significantly elevated thermal and acidic stability. These results were interpreted as suggesting that ancient life may have evolved in oceans that were much hotter and more acidic than today.<ref name=":0" />

